Section 375, PPC clearly defines rape as penetration of vagina, mouth, urethra, or anus with any body part or object, irrespective of seminal discharge--Thus, even minimal penetration qualifies as rape--The presence of spermatozoa is not required to establish this element--The offence centers on violation of victim’s bodily integrity and autonomy, not physical outcomes of act--The law emphasizes safeguarding victim’s dignity over existence of biological evidence, making absence of seminal material immaterial to strength of prosecution’s case.
Although PFSA report found no seminal material of Appellant on victim’s anal swabs but noted conceivable reasons for this such as possible use of a condom, non-ejaculation, significant delays in medico-legal examination, improper preservation or packaging of evidence, or self-cleaning and bathing by victim--As a result, report is inconclusive and neither confirms nor rules out Appellant’s involvement--In this situation, Courts are legally bound to assess other available evidence for a just determination--The Supreme Court held that DNA testing offers substantial reliability in identifying offenders, helping to secure convictions of guilty and absolve innocent--However, Court clarified that DNA evidence is corroborative in nature--It supports and reinforces other evidence but does not independently constitute conclusive proof.
