The fate of criminal trial depends upon truthfulness or otherwise of witness and, therefore, it is of paramount importance--To arrive at truth, its veracity should be judged and for that purpose cross-examination is an acid test--It tests truthfulness of statement made by a witness on oath in examination-in-chief--Its purpose is to elicit facts and materials to establish that evidence of witness is fit to be rejected.    

A layman even if intelligent and educated is not trained in this skill and cannot effectively cross-examine a witness--The Courts have thus consistently held that cross-examination by an accused himself on a prosecution witness can neither be equated nor substituted with cross-examination by a counsel.                                                                                    

There is no provision in Criminal Procedure Code, 1898, which specifically empowers trial Court to guillotine accused’s right of cross-examination--However, this does not mean that he can abuse process of law with impunity and take Court hostage--Hence, when he deliberately avoids to produce his lawyer, Court may appoint a defence counsel at State expense and proceed with trial.
