[12/25/25, 5:03:09 PM] ~ insaf sab k liey: When a person commits an offence under Section 228 of PPC in the view or presence of the court, the court has three options. The court may either proceed under Section 480 of Cr.P.C., or under Section 476 of Cr.P.C., or forward the case to learned Magistrate under Section 482 of Code of Criminal Procedure, having jurisdiction to try the same. If the court intends to proceed against the offender and complete the proceedings same day, the court shall proceed under Section 480 of Cr.P.C. and shall cause the offender to be detained in custody and at any time before rising of the court on the same day may take the cognizance of the offence and sentence the offender to a fine not exceeding two hundred rupees and in default of the payment to simple imprisonment for a term which may extend to one month. Language used in Section 480 of Cr.P.C. indicates that sentence of the fine of two hundred rupees is substantive sentence, whereas sentence of the imprisonment extending upto one month is of secondary nature, which has to be resorted to only if the offender fails to pay the fine. If the court desires to impose the sentence exceeding the above sentence, the court may have a resort to Section 476 of Cr.P.C. and try the offender in accordance with the procedure prescribed for summary trial in Chapter XXII (Sec.260 to 265 Cr.P.C.). Section 482 of Cr.P.C. deals with the situation, where court considers not to involve itself in the matter, the court may have a resort to Section 482 of Cr.P.C. and may forward the case to a Magistrate having jurisdiction to try the same. All the said provisions have always to be read in conjunction with each other.

Combined effect and critical analysis of the above said provisions is that when court proceeds under Section 480 of Cr.P.C., the said provision places a limitation on the power of the court regarding the quantum of punishment. In such case, the court may impose the sentence of fine of Rs.200/- only, or may impose the sentence of imprisonment extending upto one month, only if the fine has not been paid. If the court is of the opinion that said sentence is not appropriate in the facts and circumstances of the case, the court may initiate the proceedings against the offender under Section 476 of Cr.P.C. and shall observe entire process of summary trial prescribed under Sections 260 to 265 of Cr.P.C. Under Section 476 of Cr.P.C. a Magistrate or Civil Court may impose the sentence of imprisonment extending upto three months or fine not exceeding one thousand rupees, or both. 

