[12/25/25, 5:03:12 PM] ~ insaf sab k liey: For a proper resolution of the controversy, it is necessary to refer to the statutory framework. Licence No.11/D/95 was issued under Rule 253 of the Motor Vehicles Rules, 1969 (hereinafter, “the Rules, 1969”). The proviso to Rule 253(2) ibid is of particular significance: “no place which is privately owned shall be notified as a Stand unless the application is made by the owner of that place.” This inextricably links the entitlement to hold a recognized stand to the ownership or lawful control of the land in question. 

 The legal character of the licence must also be underscored. A licence is merely a permission to do something which would otherwise be unlawful. It is a privilege1, not a property right. Licence in question, therefore, never created a vested, indefeasible or permanent right in favour of the petitioners. Consequently, upon the death of one of the original licensees, Khawaja Muhammad Yousaf, the licence did not automatically devolve upon his legal heirs as a heritable right. 

 Rule 266 of the Rules, 1969 is also relevant to the case in hand. The plain language of Rule 266(1) ibid confers upon the Regional Transport Authority a broad regulatory power to revoke an order permitting establishment of a stand where conditions of the order have been breached, management is unsatisfactory or its continuance would not be in the public interest. These are regulatory, not proprietary, powers; their exercise is concerned with the proper administration and management of public vehicle stands in the interest of the travelling public and public order. It is evident that the licence in question was issued and periodically renewed in circumstances where (a) one of the original licensees had passed away; (b) the underlying land which formed the basis for the stand remains joint and unpartitioned among legal heirs; and (c) at least one co-owner (respondent No.5) expressly objected to renewal. When the proviso to Rule 253  of the Rules, 1969 is read together with Rule 266, a clear picture emerges that a privately owned place must be the subject of an application by the owner (or by those lawfully entitled) and, if that foundational condition is disputed, the competent authority is entitled to take regulatory steps (including revocation) to prevent the continuance of a concession that may aggravate disputes, endanger public order or amount to administrative impropriety. 

  In the above legal and factual backdrop, the impugned order of revocation falls within the Authority’s regulatory power. The Transport Authority correctly identified the defect of the licence continuing in a deceased person’s name and the untenability of the arrangement due to the ownership dispute. It surely is not the province of the licensing authority to adjudicate the proprietary rights among the heirs. Such disputes are for the civil court to resolve. The petitioners’ remedy, therefore, lies in seeking a determination of their respective shares before the civil court. Upon obtaining a decree or settlement that establishes a clear and undisputed entitlement, they may apply afresh for a licence in accordance with law. 

